\begin_layout Subsection*
Self-isolation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Self-isolation is a challenge in informal settlements, where households
 consist of a single (often small) space, water is collected at designated
 locations, sanitation facilities are communal and food supplies are scarce.
 We considered the possibility of those showing symptoms self-isolating
 in individual tents in dedicated parts of the camps.
 We simulated this intervention with various numbers of isolation tents
 per camp, ranging from 10 to 2000 for a camp of 2000 people (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Interventions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-2).
 In addition, we modeled the role of carers dedicated to providing for isolated
 individuals (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Interventions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-2a).
 Interactions between carers and isolated individuals were restricted to
 buffer zones, which we envisioned as open spaces, with guidelines in place
 to limit occupancy to 4 individuals wearing masks, with 2 meters separating
 individuals, where the probability of transmission is reduced by 80% (see
 Supplementary Material).
 In considering one carer per isolated individual with one contact per day,
 we do not neglect their probability of infecting the rest of the camp.
 We also considered minimum time intervals for individuals to recognize
 their symptoms: with means of 12, 24 and 48 hours (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Interventions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-2b).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With only 10 tents for a camp of 2000 people (i.e.
 1 tent for every 200 people), self-isolation yields a modest decrease in
 the probability of observing an outbreak (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Panel2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
